english:
  title: Preface to Sending Off Master Gusan, an Old Monk
  author: Gang Hee-maeng
  language: eng
  text: |-
    The virtue of a gentleman seeps deep into the hearts of men. Thus the affection and admiration they bear him knows no distinction between past and present, between the living and the dead. For it flows from the heart's delight and sincere reverence—his very name commands respect, his traces inspire treasured love, and even those who walked with him or received his guidance hold him dear. How could there be any pretense in such regard? My elder brother, Master Injae, was such a gentleman. Whether people were noble or humble, wise or simple, once they kept company with him, all submitted to his magnanimity, their praise never ceasing from their lips. After he departed this world, from the ministers in court down to the common folk in the streets, all who had seen his face wept in sorrow, saying, "The world has lost its elder." How deeply his virtue touched men's hearts! In the summer of the year Mucha, when I arrived at the chambers of Great Master Hongil at Heungcheon Temple, there appeared a monk of noble countenance and clear spirit—a true practitioner of the Way. Upon seeing me, he seemed stricken with sorrow and emotion. After a moment, he spoke: "I came to know your elder brother, Master Injae, who loved me most deeply—so much that he painted a landscape for me with his own hand. I treasure it still. Alas, how swift is impermanence! In the midst of death and life, being and non-being, I have lost a cherished friend forever. Can one escape the bonds of worldly feeling? Seeing you, I glimpse something of Master Injae's visage. My longing overwhelms me, and I cannot hold back. If you would show me the kindness Master Injae showed me, then though I have lost him, I would gain him again." With that, he withdrew a scroll of poetry, its top left blank, and asked me to write a preface.

    His words moved me, his sentiment grieved me. I reflected: When men form bonds through profit, profit's end brings coldness. When they bind through power, power's loss brings separation. Clouds become rain, rain returns to clouds—morning friends become evening enemies. Such is the way of men. How could we speak of such things without shame? Yet this monk has already cut through delusion, severed the bonds of attachment, and cast aside even kinship's closest ties. What more of friendship? That he now mourns my brother and transfers his affection to me to such a degree—surely my brother possessed that virtue which penetrates the human heart. How else could he so move this monk? There must be reason in it. That the monk was favored by my brother was not without cause.

    Since my brother abandoned me, I have stood alone, my days heavy with longing. I cannot hear his voice or see his face, yet in meeting one like this monk who knew him, my heart finds some solace. Thus I recite this verse:

    *Where is the distant spring now? Sound and face forever lost to me.
    The purple lilac falls—the spring branch stands bare.
    The geese's line breaks—how hard to join it once again.
    I cradle myself and grieve; my heart aches in every corner.
    The world is vast, its people numberless,
    Yet you, my brother, remain forever hard to meet.
    Suddenly encountering your friend, the longings of years return.
    As I speak of old times, tears fall first.*

    When the monk heard these words, we wept together, and he asked me to set them down as this preface.
  footnotes:
  - key: ''
    value: Injae (仁齋) was the author's deceased elder brother, whose virtue and character had left a lasting impression on all who knew him, including this Buddhist monk.
  - key: ''
    value: Heungcheon Temple (興天寺) was a significant Buddhist temple where the author encountered this monk.
  - key: ''
    value: The poem's imagery draws on classical Chinese references to separation and longing—the 'purple lilac' alludes to the famous story of two brothers and their fraternal bond, while the 'geese's line' symbolizes the breaking of harmonious connections.
  - key: ''
    value: The contrast between worldly relationships based on profit or power, and the monk's spiritual bond based on genuine virtue, forms the ethical heart of this preface.
